---
title: 'The Weight of Silence'
date: '2026-03-05'
category: 'poetry'
excerpt: 'What silence carries that words never could'
---

There are silences that speak
louder than arguments ever did —
the kind that settle into rooms
after someone leaves
and stays.

I have learned to read them
the way you read weather.
A heavy silence means something broke.
A soft one means
someone is thinking about you
and hasn't found the words yet.

The worst kind
is the one that used to be noise —
a chair that scraped,
a name called from another room,
a laugh that knew
exactly when to arrive.

Now just the weight of it.
Sitting where the sound used to be.

---
### Expressions
- **"read them the way you read weather"** — silence, like weather, has moods. You learn to feel it before it hits.
- **"a laugh that knew exactly when to arrive"** — some people have a presence so familiar, even their joy felt like punctuation in your day.
